gdio, Enrique, Felipe, Francisco, Jose Luis, Julio, Ruben.  Jewish Hyman, Isadore.","Spanish and Galician: unexplained.","French and English (Middlesex): from the Old French personal name <i>Ballon</i>, <i>Ballun</i>, derived from the oblique stem of ancient Germanic <i>Ballo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>bal</i>, presumably meaning ‘torment, spitefulness’ (see   Ballard  )."]},{"name":"Bald","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Inge, Karl-Heinz, Konrad, Kurt, Otto.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i>, or a short form of various compound names such as   Baldwin  , formed with the first element <i>bald</i> ‘bold, strong’.","Scottish and English: from the Norman personal name <i>Bald(e)</i>, <i>Baud(e)</i>, occasionally <i>Bold</i>, a short form of the common ancient Germanic personal names   Baldwin   or <i>Baldric</i>, or possibly a survival of Old English <i>Beald</i> (compare   Balding  ); the relevant element in each of these is <i>b(e)ald</i> ‘brave’. As a hereditary surname it seems to have died out in England but survives in Scotland."]},{"name":"Ballor","meanings":["Altered form of French   Ballard   2, reflecting the characteristic Canadian and American French rounding of the <i>-ard</i> ending. It is found mainly in MI."]},{"name":"Bollard","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire) and Irish: probably a variant of   Ballard  . According to MacLysaght, this is a surname of Dutch origin which was taken to Ireland early in the 18th century.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bolohard</i>, composed of the elements <i>bolo</i> ‘friend, brother’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’."]}]},{"name":"MP","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Chung, Chang, Jian, Li, Tong, Bin, Chao, Cheng, Chin, Chuan, Der, Feng, Fung, Hua.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 穆, meaning ‘solemnity, virtue’: (i) from Mu (穆), posthumous title of the Duke Mu of Song (died 720  BC ), the 14th ruler of the state of Song (located in present-day Shangqiu in Henan province). He earned the title Mu, 穆, because of his virtue during his reign. (ii) from the Qiu Mu Ling (丘穆陵) family, members of the Xianbei ethnic group in ancient northern China, who changed their original surname to Mu (穆) during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from Mu (穆), posthumous title of the Duke Mu of Lu (died 377  BC ), ruler of the state of Lu (located in present-day Shandong province).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 慕: (i) said to be traced back to Yu Mu (虞慕), ancestor of the legendary Emperor Shun (<i>c.</i> 23rd century  BC ). (ii) shortened form of the compound surname Mu-Rong (慕容), a surname from the Xianbei and Tuyuhun ethnic group in northern China. (iii) a surname from Korean and Jurchen ethnic groups in northeastern China."],"variants":[{"name":"Moo","meanings":["Chinese: variant of   Mu  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 巫, possibly based on its Hakka pronunciation, see   Wu   4.","Burmese (Karen): variant of   Mu   9."]},{"name":"Wu","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ming, Wei, Jian, Mei, Jing, Ying, Bin, Hong, Jin, Ping, Ching, Wen.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 吳, meaning ‘big, large’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from Wu (吳), the name of a state (located in present-day Jiangsu province) which was granted to Tai Bo, the first son of King Tai of Zhou (died <i>c.</i> 1146  BC ). After it was annexed by the state of Yue in 473  BC , people from the state adopted 吳 (Wu) as their surname. (ii) from the placename Yu (虞) (located in present-day Shanxi province). Because Yu (虞) had a similar pronunciation to that of Wu (吳) in ancient Chinese, some people acquired Wu (吳) instead of Yu (虞) as their surname."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Ballard MP was born about 1330, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Fulco Ballard, was 82 and his mother, Esther Preston, was 36. He had at least 2 sons with Alice Gregory. He died about 1382, in Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England, at the age of 54."},"et":{"about 1330–about 1382":"umbes 1330–umbes 1382","1330–1382":"1330–1382","1335–1395":"1335–1395","1358–1420":"1358–1420","1370–1415":"1370–1415","1250–1346":"1250–1346","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","about 1382":"umbes 1382","1330":"1330","BEF 1346":"enne 1346","1395":"1395","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1415":"1415","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1346":"1346","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1420":"1420","about 1330":"umbes 1330","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamsh